## The model

Simple linear regression assumes that the outcome $y_i$ is a linear function
of a single predictor $x_i$, plus Gaussian noise:

$$
y_i = \alpha + \beta\, x_i + \varepsilon_i,
\qquad \varepsilon_i \sim \text{Normal}(0, \sigma)
$$

Equivalently, written as a probability model:

$$
y_i \sim \text{Normal}(\alpha + \beta\, x_i,\; \sigma)
$$

There are three parameters to estimate:

| Parameter | Meaning | Constraint |
|---|---|---|
| $\alpha$ | Intercept: expected $y$ when $x = 0$ | none |
| $\beta$ | Slope: change in expected $y$ per unit increase in $x$ | none |
| $\sigma$ | Residual SD: unexplained variation | $> 0$ |

: Parameters of simple linear regression. {#tbl-params}

